          "body": "The psalm closes not with a doxology but with a description: 'who turned the rock into a pool of water, the flint into a fountain of water' (114:8). The reference is to Meribah and Massah (Exodus 17:1-7; Numbers 20:1-13), where Israel complained of thirst and God commanded Moses to strike the rock — from which water flowed in the wilderness. The double image (rock/pool, flint/fountain) intensifies the miracle by choosing the hardest possible stones. Flint (*challamish*) was the hardest material in the ancient Near East, used for cutting tools and weapons; it has no capacity to hold or release water. Yet this is precisely the material God chose to make a fountain. The closing image answers the command of verse 7: why should the earth tremble? Because this God turns death into life, aridity into abundance, and the hardest thing in nature into the softest gift. Paul reads this water-from-rock typologically in 1 Corinthians 10:4 — 'the rock was Christ' — the sustaining provision in the wilderness is the pre-incarnate Christ, making the psalm's closing image an implicit Christology."
